{"type":"text","timestamp":1780728251699,"sessionID":"ses_16456759bffexNlpdmr83lyyd3","part":{"id":"prt_e9bac1adb001o2nouoGlNjt9Mq","messageID":"msg_e9bab93dc001EYokqQrBXKehGr","sessionID":"ses_16456759bffexNlpdmr83lyyd3","type":"text","text":"## Mechanism\nMemClaw separates lifecycle into status-only archive, soft-delete grace, and later hard purge.\n\nArchive criteria are SQL predicates on live memories. `memory_archive_expired` marks active, non-deleted rows as `outdated` when `ts_valid_end < NOW()` and limits each batch to 500 (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1575`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1590`). `memory_archive_stale` marks active, non-deleted rows as `archived` when they are older than `stale_days`, have `recall_count = 0`, and `weight < max_weight` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1606`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1628`). Archive operations are idempotent because rows leave the `status = 'active'` candidate set after the first update (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1596`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1636`).\n\nSoft-delete is not a hard delete. `memory_soft_delete` sets `deleted_at = now()` and `status = \"deleted\"` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418`). Hot-path updates reject soft-deleted rows and keep `deleted_at IS NULL` guards on update statements so later writes do not resurrect deleted rows (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:486`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:526`).\n\nPurge is the hard-delete phase. `memory_purge_soft_deleted` deletes rows whose `deleted_at` is older than `retention_days`; its docstring says this removes the memory row plus embedding, entity links, and idempotency response cache lines through FKs (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1653`). The DELETE predicate is `deleted_at IS NOT NULL AND deleted_at < NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day' * :retention_days` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1674`). Purge fanout targets only tenants with soft-deleted rows older than the maximum retention window, using DB clock to avoid client-clock drift (`core-api/src/core_api/services/tenants.py:25`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/tenants.py:37`).\n\nRetention is a bounded policy snapshot. `LifecyclePurgeRequest` carries `retention_days`; the comments state fanout reads org settings at cron time and consumers trust that snapshot (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:1`, `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:4`). The configured range is 1-30 days (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:21`), settings validation reuses those constants (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:340`), and unresolved config defaults to 30 days (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:537`).\n\nSupersession is status/link lifecycle, not deletion. `Memory` has `status` and `supersedes_id` fields (`common/models/memory.py:56`, `common/models/memory.py:79`). `memory_update_status` can set, clear, or CAS-check `supersedes_id` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:538`). Default search excludes `outdated` and `conflicted` memories while allowing explicit `status_filter` inspection (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1149`).\n\nLifecycle audit is pre-published, stateful, and sticky-success. `LifecycleAudit` stores `org_id`, `action`, `triggered_by`, `started_at`, `finished_at`, `status`, `stats`, and `error_message` (`common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:24`). The fanout path creates the audit row before publishing the event so publish failure leaves an observable `pending` row (`core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:99`). Handlers move the same audit row through `in_progress`, `success`, or `failure`, and SQL ops are described as safe under redelivery (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127`). Finalization stamps `finished_at` only for terminal states and blocks updates once status is already `success`, preserving original stats on redelivery (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4350`).\n\n## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory (027/004)\n1. **Claim** · Tombstone/grace first, hard-delete later. **Evidence** · MemClaw soft-delete sets `deleted_at` and `status=\"deleted\"` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418`); hard purge only deletes rows whose `deleted_at` is older than retention (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1674`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Tombstones must be excluded from active reads everywhere or deleted causal edges can reappear. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The multi-tenant wrapper does not transfer, but the local invariant does: every active causal-edge delete should first persist a tombstone timestamp/status, and hard-delete should be a separate retention sweep.\n\n2. **Claim** · Lifecycle audit should be append-observable and sticky-success. **Evidence** · Audit rows start `pending` and expose terminal states (`common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:3`); finalization blocks overwriting `success` on redelivery (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4350`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A full audit table may be too heavy for SQLite unless scoped to lifecycle/tombstone sweeps. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit does not need Pub/Sub, but it benefits from local audit rows for tombstone sweeps: run id, action, cutoff, counts, status, error.\n\n3. **Claim** · Persist the retention cutoff/parameter snapshot with the lifecycle request. **Evidence** · Purge payload carries `retention_days` as the per-org policy snapshot read at fanout time (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:4`); fanout resolves purge kwargs from config (`core-api/src/core_api/services/lifecycle_audit.py:227`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A changed setting mid-run will not affect the in-flight sweep, so the UI/docs must make snapshot semantics clear. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user SQLite has no org fanout, but should still record the effective retention cutoff used by each sweep for reproducibility.\n\n4. **Claim** · Idempotent lifecycle predicates should make retries harmless without special recovery code. **Evidence** · Archive only updates `status='active'` live rows (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1596`); purge only deletes already-soft-deleted rows beyond cutoff (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1679`); tenant purge explicitly documents rerun safety (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1701`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Batch limits can leave partial backlog, so audit stats must distinguish partial progress from completion. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit local sweeps can use SQLite predicates that naturally no-op after success, avoiding bespoke retry flags.\n\n5. **Claim** · Supersession should hide stale facts by default while preserving inspectable lineage. **Evidence** · `supersedes_id` records lineage (`common/models/memory.py:79`); default search filters out `outdated` and `conflicted` rows but explicit status filtering can include them (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1149`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Over-filtering can hide historical rationale unless explain/debug views bypass the filter. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit’s causal graph already has supersedes semantics; MemClaw reinforces separating “not active for retrieval” from “safe to purge.”\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy MemClaw’s multi-tenant fanout machinery. The cron service only POSTs a fanout endpoint while core-api enumerates orgs and publishes per-org events (`core-operations/src/core_operations/tasks.py:1`, `core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:138`). Spec Kit is local/single-user and should use an in-process sweep, not Pub/Sub or REST fanout.\n\nDo not copy fleet scoping. MemClaw carries optional `fleet_id` through lifecycle payloads and SQL predicates (`common/events/lifecycle_archive_request.py:31`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1584`). Spec Kit has no fleet dimension.\n\nDo not copy per-org retention settings. MemClaw validates `lifecycle.memory_retention_days` per org (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:329`). Spec Kit should use one local retention policy unless a concrete multi-profile need appears.\n\nDo not copy distributed-scheduler dedup windows for local SQL lifecycle. MemClaw’s 23-hour dedup gate is for pipeline ops and cron double-fires (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:100`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4376`). Local retention/tombstone sweeps should rely on idempotent SQL predicates plus audit, not time-window distributed dedup.\n\nDo not copy Postgres-specific partial-index assumptions directly. MemClaw uses Postgres partial indexes for live rows and purgeable rows (`common/models/memory.py:118`, `common/models/memory.py:131`). SQLite can use partial indexes too, but the exact pgvector/Postgres indexing strategy is fleet-storage machinery.\n\n## Open questions\nShould Spec Kit add a compact `lifecycle_audit` table, or attach sweep audit metadata to existing memory/tombstone maintenance records?\n\nWhat is the exact retention period for causal-edge tombstones before hard-delete, and should it differ from expired governed memory retention?\n\nShould hard-delete sweeps be bounded by row count per run, and if so how should partial completion be represented in local audit?\n\nWhich read paths currently need tombstone filters for causal edges, and is there a test proving deleted edges cannot reappear through graph traversal?\n\nShould superseded-but-not-deleted causal edges get a distinct status from tombstoned/deleted edges so lineage remains inspectable?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"087\",\"focus\":\"lifecycle / retention / archive / purge / tombstones\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: tombstone/grace first, hard-delete later\",\"ADAPT: sticky lifecycle audit with effective retention snapshot\",\"ADAPT: idempotent lifecycle predicates for retries\"],\"sources\":[\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1575\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315\",\"common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:24\",\"core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:99\"]}","time":{"start":1780728208091,"end":1780728251696},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0c9bd35e3941ac3d016a23c1900c1881919984cba7309f0447","phase":"final_answer"}}}}
